6E3-58AE-4081-A471-C2BCCCAE21C1</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Oliver</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>James</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF00379X%2F1"><gtr:id>F39B5863-4FA2-4202-B7A9-4A6FFA571370</gtr:id><gtr:title>Standards of Evidence for Assessing Public Service Performance</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F00379X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The need for assessments of public service performance to be, in some sense, 'evidence based' is generally uncontroversial but standards of evidence are not straightforward to develop or implement. Standards of evidence relate to the production and use of evidence that is fit for purpose. Purposes include internal management, use in oversight of public bodies, political accountability by a range of stakeholders, and enabling choice of services by users in quasi-markets. Standards are important because they set what is deemed acceptable evidence, frameworks of standards set the trade-offs between standards and shape what evidence is taken into account in these decision making contexts. The research undertaken during the fellowship (part-time) will address the practice and potential practice of the contemporary public sector, drawing particularly on the experience in England where there has been a sizeable public investment in performance assessment. The fellowship will generate synergies between several projects on the Programme, fill gaps in knowledge and develop an empirically supported theoretical approach on these themes.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</g